==Statistics and records==
{{details|Gillingham F.C. records}}
[[Image:GFCrecord.jpg|400px|thumb|right|League positions since the 1950<U+2013>51 season.<br />''Horizontal grey lines indicate league divisions.'']]
Goalkeeper [[Ron Hillyard]] holds the record for Gillingham appearances, having played 657 matches in all competitions between 1974 and 1990,<ref>{{cite book |   last= Triggs |   title=The Men Who Made Gillingham Football Club | pages=p158}}</ref> while the record for appearances solely in the [[Football League]] is held by another goalkeeper, [[John Simpson (footballer born 1933)|John Simpson]], with 571 betwen 1957 and 1972.<ref name="SB" />  [[Brian Yeo]] is the club's all-time leading league goalscorer, having scored a total of 136 goals between 1963 and 1975.<ref name="yeo" />  He also jointly holds the record for the most goals scored in a single season, having scored 31 goals in the [[1973-74 in English football|1973<U+2013>74]] season,<ref name="yeo">{{cite book |   last= Triggs |   title=The Men Who Made Gillingham Football Club | pages=p344}}</ref> equalling the record set by [[Ernie Morgan]] in [[1954-55 in English football|1954&ndash;55]].<ref>{{cite book |   last= Triggs |   title=The Men Who Made Gillingham Football Club | pages=p226}}</ref>  The highest number of goals scored by a player in a single game is the six registered by [[Fred Cheesmur]] against [[Merthyr Town F.C.|Merthyr Town]] in April 1930.<ref>{{cite book |   last= Triggs |   title=The Men Who Made Gillingham Football Club |pages=p349}}</ref>

The club's record home attendance is 23,002, for an [[FA Cup]] match against [[Queen's Park Rangers F.C.|QPR]] on 10 January 1948,<ref name="SB">{{Cite web
| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/team_records.sd?teamid=1098
| title = Gillingham all time records
| accessdate = 2007-04-11
| publisher = [[Soccerbase]]
}}</ref> a record which will almost certainly never be broken unless the club relocates to a larger ground, given that Priestfield Stadium's current capacity is approximately half that figure.

The team's biggest ever professional win was a 10-0 defeat of  [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]] in September 1987,<ref name="SB" />
although they had previously registered a 12-1 win against [[Gloucester City F.C.|Gloucester City]] in the [[Southern Football League|Southern League]] in November 1946.<ref name="GFCHist" />

The Gills hold the record for the fewest goals conceded by a team in the course of a 46 game season,<ref>[http://www.football-league.premiumtv.co.uk/page/RecordGoals/0,,10794,00.html The official Football League website] lists this achievement in second place on the overall list of teams who have conceded the fewest goals in a season, behind [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], who conceded 16 in the 1978<U+2013>79 season, however, as evidenced by [http://www.soccerbase.com/league2.sd?competitionid=5&seasonid=108&x=17&y=6 the final 1978<U+2013>79 First Division table], Liverpool played only 42 matches, giving Gillingham the record for a 46-match season.</ref> having conceded just 20 in the [[1995-96 in English football|1995<U+2013>96]] season,<ref name="FCHD" /> during which goalkeeper [[Jim Stannard]] kept 29 clean sheets.<ref name="SB">{{Cite web
| url = http://www.football-league.premiumtv.co.uk/page/RecordGoals/0,,10794,00.html
| title = Football League Records: Goals
| accessdate = 2007-04-10
| publisher = [[The Football League]]
}}</ref>

==Rivalries==
Due to Gillingham's position geographically, there have traditionally not been fierce local rivalries with neighbouring clubs, as the closest other League teams are based in [[London]] and [[Essex]].  The closest League team is [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]], across the mouth of the [[River Thames]].  A 2003 fan survey<ref>{{Cite web
| url = http://www.footballfanscensus.com/issueresults/Club_Rivalries_Uncovered_Results.pdf
| title = Rivalry Uncovered!
| accessdate = 2007-04-11
| publisher = The [[Football Fans Census]]
}}</ref> revealed that Gillingham (along with [[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]], [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]], [[Torquay United F.C.|Torquay United]] and [[York City F.C.|York City]]) were not considered to be rivals by supporters of any other club.

[[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] are currently considered to be the closest the Gills have to local rivals.<ref name="FGG" />  [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] are seen by many fans as the club's biggest rivals, stemming from bad-tempered matches between the two teams in 1979 and 1987.<ref>{{Cite web
| url = http://www.gillingham-mad.co.uk/news/loadfeat.asp?cid=EDW3&id=183555
| title = Swindon Town: 25 years of hate
| accessdate = 2007-04-11
| publisher = www.gillingham-mad.co.uk
}}</ref>  While Swindon fans generally do not consider Gillingham their biggest rivals, there was violence when they met at Priestfield in the [[2005-06 in English football|2005<U+2013>06]] season, their first meeting since a promotion play-off match in 1987.<ref>{{Cite web
| url = http://archive.thisiswiltshire.co.uk/2006/1/17/259405.html
| title = Town set to pay price for crowd trouble
| accessdate = 2007-04-11
| publisher = Swindon Advertiser
}}</ref>  Following their promotion in 1989, [[Maidstone United F.C.|Maidstone United]] became Kent's second League side.  A friendly rivalry with Gillingham developed over the following seasons, with several Kent derby games, until Maidstone's financial troubles forced them to resign from the League in 1992.<ref>{{Cite web
| url = http://www.leicestercity-mad.co.uk/news/loadfeat.asp?cid=ED12&id=179902
| title = Opposition Chat - Gillingham
| accessdate = 2007-04-11
| publisher = www.leicestercity-mad.co.uk
}}</ref>

==Gillingham in popular culture==
The 2005 film ''[[Green Street]]'' (known as ''Green Street Hooligans'' in the USA) makes use of action sequences filmed during a match between Gillingham and [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]], although for unknown reasons the dialogue states that the team playing West Ham is [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]].<ref>{{Cite web
| url = http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0385002/
| title = Hooligans
| publisher = [[Internet Movie Database]]
| accessdate = 2007-04-12
}}</ref>

==See also==
